social_posts.post_text:
This is gonna be long - so stick with me for a minute….

The past few weeks I haven’t gotten as much writing done as I had hoped, and and I was feeling pretty bad about it.  Between the road trip with the kids, JP out of town traveling for work every week, and just life - I can't seem to get my head above water.  Let alone string sentences together fluidly. 

The other day it all came boiling over when I was on a group zoom call listening to a fairly well-known author share writing advice.  She shared that her first book was written right after she had given birth, and that she never had more than 15-minutes at a time to write.  Encouraging us "That it can be done. You just have to find those 15-minute windows - at school pick-up, the doctor's office, getting up earlier/staying up later.  That you just have to push." 

And I thought to myself....wow, this is really terrible advice.  No wonder I was feeling bad about myself.  Messages like this are why we're all running around exhausted and feeling like we didn't "do enough".

And it's happens ALL the time.  everywhere, in every industry, in every room, on every social media platform.  The message of achieving and pushing - not showing the stress,
and heartache that comes along with it. 

And I for one want something different.  I’m tired.  I don’t want to end the year feeling like once again, I could have done more. 

And I don’t want that for you either. The next few weeks you don’t have to say “yes” to anything you don’t want to do.  Personally or professionally.  You can skip the holiday party, or not send Xmas cards, or not finish that book. 

And it will all still be ok.  There’s no need to push.  You can choose to do things differently.  Life can be easy.  There is no race.  No score.  You’re doing great.  Slow down.  It’s ok to just enjoy your life sometimes.  After all, it’s why we’re here.

I remember when this is what I wished for…..

All of it.  The kids, our life, a holiday like this.  And now..it’s here. 

And I’m so tired of letting it flash before me.  Missing it.  Because I’m stuck in my own damn head.

I just hit publish on my first blog post of the year.  Sharing what I’m craving for 2023….

More peace.  More contentment.  And more enjoying this life I’ve been so busy building, I forgot to actually enjoy. 

🤍 kids back at school today. I’m back to writing.  Easing into this year slowly.  Hope you are too. 

Full blog post linked in my bio and in stories 🤍

For the rest of the month of January, I’m committed to taking better care of myself.  Getting back to the basics. The things I know how me calm my mind and clear my energy. 

And if your need a little motivation, or to change up your energy - join me!

Here’s what I’m doing..
- 8 hours of sleep (bed at 9, up at 5)
- at least 15 minutes of meditation before starting my day
- 30 minutes of movement every day to clear my energy 

Nothing complicated.  No programs or equipment or special plan.  Just sleep.  Stillness.  And movement

Because I know that when I commit, and I mean really commit to feeling my best and taking care of me - my whole world changes.  And I want that for all of us 🤍

Sharing my full morning routine over on the blog today and getting really specific.  Answering all your questions from how I manage to get 8 hours of sleep at night, how I handle it with my kids running around, down to what tea I drink.

My hope is that this is NOT a formula for you, but rather inspires you to step back and think about how you want to start your own day.  How you want to feel.  If you want to make any changes - and if so, what.

If anything I’ve learned after having some type of morning routine for almost a decade it’s that I get to choose how I show up each day. And that while life will never slow down, get easier, or be less stressful - how I respond to it is up to me.

What about you?  Do you follow any type of routine in the am?  Have you ever thought about changing up your mornings?  I’m curious.  Share with us what’s work for you and maybe what’s not….

You can find the full blog post with all the details on my morning routine linked in my bio and in stories ✨

One of my go to lunches these days - big nourishing bowls of love.  This one is filled with everything from sweet potatoes and lentils to pickled onions (which are insane) and avocado - all topped with a spicy ginger lime dressing.  I’ve been making this at least once a week.  It’s ridiculously good.  Trust me.  Full recipe linked in my bio, in stories and over on the blog 😘

I just hit publish on a blog post sharing my experience trying to better understand and balance my hormones.  I turn 44 next month, and this year I felt a major shift in my body.  But every doctor I spoke to told me my symptoms were “normal” and just a part of aging.

But I don’t think that has to be the case.  We can do better than that.  I’ve been on a journey this year to learn more about my body and what I can do to continue to feel well and good in my skin, even as I age.

This is something EVERY woman experiences and goes through - and yet something so many of us struggle to have any clear answers on or get any clear direction.

I’m hoping that in sharing my experience into my hormone health it may help even just a few of you in where to begin with your own journey. 

Because we all deserve to feel good in our skin, at every age.  And just because something is “common”, it doesn’t mean it’s good….

Full post linked in my bio and in stories, and as always, just thanks for being here 

Xoxo

I’ve been thinking a lot about why we moved here lately.  Why we uprooted 6 people when we didn’t have to.  Why we chose to leave a home we loved to live in a rental.  We we chose to have kids who are about to enter high school start over fresh.  Why in many ways we chose to complicate our lives, instead of staying in the comfort of the familiar.

And then I have a morning like this.  When for a moment it all feels so clear.

When the colors of the sky seem to change just for me.  When the sound of the ocean feels as if it’s beating in my chest, just for me.  When the universe seems to be using everything in her power to say THIS is where you belong.  Right here.  Right now. 

And something new in you awakens.

Maybe all of this life stuff we do.  The kids, the houses, the jobs.  Has nothing to do with the actual thing itself.  And instead is just simply an opportunity for us to become something new.

To expand

To Experience 

To Awaken

Panama photo dump.  Half way through the my time here in Panamá and already planning my next trip back.  This place is truly magical.  I came to @sansararesort because one of my favorite teachers, @clairemarkyoga was leading a retreat here and it’s been so good for my soul.

I realized last night that in 15 years, this is the first time I’ve ever been away from JP and the kids.  Ever.  In 15 years.  When I first booked this trip it felt so indulgent (money, time away from kids, asking JP to handle more, etc) but I knew I had to go.  I needed to do something not as a wife or as a mother - but as me.  A woman.  Who knows she deserves this time and more importantly this experience. 

I heard lyrics in a song while I was here…travel brings you closer to home.

And I feel that so deeply. 

Feeling more at home..in me 🤍

Ok, off to yoga.  Xoxo

….I made peace with me.

I stopped finding fault with me, 
I stopped finding fault with you.

I stopped looking for reason for feel bad,
And I started looking for reasons to feel good

- the one and only Abraham Hicks (ps, the book “ask and it is given” by her CHANGED my life ✨)

Home after an incredible 9 days away.  So many “ah-ha” moments as I’m sitting here drinking my tea this am, of what I’m taking home from this experience.  None of it in any order, or thought through.  Just what’s on my heart this am….

* I want to have more FUN.  To stop taking myself and everything so seriously. To laugh at myself more.
* to let people in ❤️ open myself up to new friendships 
* to let go of this need for productivity, and instead trust that my body knows what it needs, and just do what feels GOOD in the moment
* to say “yes” to more things for the pure sake of enjoyment.  The trip, the bike ride, the brownie, the extra swim. “Yes” to more of life.  I’m tired of denying myself things.
* to see myself the way others do 🤍 to trust that I have gifts to share more than I do
* and to more travel and new perspectives….

Two things…

1 - wishing the happiest of birthdays to my very favorite person on earth.  There’s no one else I’d want to do this thing called life with. Happy birthday @jprexing 

And 2 - I just hit publish on a new blog post about how JP and I make our partnership work.  I get asked a lot how we juggle things and make it all work.  And I’ll be honest, it hasn’t always been easy.  It’s taken us years to learn how to both show up for each other and our kids 100%, and I’m really proud of how far we’ve come.  My hope is that by sharing a little bit of our story and struggle over the years it helps maybe one of you feel a little less alone in yours.  Marriage (or any relationship) and parenting is not easy, and there’s no “one way” to make it work.  I think you just do the best you can, ask for what you need, and in turn do the same for your partner….

We spend so much time/energy worrying about the outside world that I think sometimes we overlook or take for granted what’s right here in our homes. 

I love this quote from Mother Theresa…

“If you want to change the world, go home and love your family”

🤍🤍🤍🤍

I have an old story I’ve carried for far too long that I’m ready to let go of.  One that tells me I’m a fraud.  Unworthy & unqualified to lead women in their own liberation and expansion, when I’m struggling to do the same myself.

…Who am I to teach about self-love, when I’m still learning to embody it myself.

To see myself fully, with all my flaws, and not just accept them, but radically LOVE who I am, exactly as I am in this moment. 

For the past six months or so I’ve been growing & evolving into a new version of me.  One that’s outgrown the old version of me I’ve shared here online, and I’ve been struggling to find my new voice…

To say…look at me, join me, as I find my way.  As I learn what self-love looks like in this new chapter.  As I manage my way through this new awakening and find my new identity.  Come find yours alongside me.

It felt too raw.  Too vulnerable. Not polished enough.  I like things neat and pretty, and my insides haven’t felt neat and pretty. 

And I’ve been scared.  Scared that I’d lose my credibility.  That I’d lose my expertise if I wasn’t farther along. 

But the truth is, I may never be.  This work is never-ending.

So for now, I’m learning to be a student and a teacher all at once.  To teach self-love, while also learning how to embody it in my own life.

That I am allowed to be a leader and a work in progress.

That we can be both. 

That my gift is being in both….

(…thank you to @kellybrock for helping me see this today - may we be leaders and a work in progress ✨)
Felt like it needed a permanent place in the grid.  May we all learn to be leaders, AND a work in progress.  Learning to live in both
Been home almost a week from @sansararesort and still on a high.

When JP and I decided to move to the west coast we made a conscious choice to say “yes” to more travel and experiences.  We’ve made it a priority.  So our time, energy, money goes to doing things, experiencing things - as individuals, as a couple and as a family.

When we moved here we sold our home and most of our furniture and belongings…and it’s changed our perspective a lot on what we value.  Where our time was going and what we really want with our life.

I’m not sure this season of saying “yes” to everything will last forever - but for today…it feels really good. 

…and a huge thank you to @out_inthefield for a gorgeous evening.  Truly magical

We like to believe there is going to be some big moment that comes and changes our lives, or who we are.  But in reality….

It’s the small, simple choices we make every single day that have the biggest impact.

The way we calm our minds
Nourish our bodies
The people we love and surround ourselves with 
The stories we tell ourselves every day when we look in the mirror.

Its those simple choices that make up our lives.

And every day, we have a chance to start over and choose again.

What comes next is up to one thing….YOU

When was the last time you thanked your body for being here?  For being alive?  For carrying you around this amazing place we call earth? 

For years, I wasted so much time finding flaws with my body.  Talking negatively to her.  Shaming her.  For growing, changing, aging.  Every time I’d put on clothes, or look in the mirror, silently wishing to myself that something about me was different.

I wasted so many years not being present and IN my body, appreciating the amazingness that stood before me.

As I was packing today for our trip I took a moment as I walked past my mirror and apologized to my body for all the years I wasn’t good to her, and thanked her for all the years she’s carried me around and all that she has allowed me to feel, see, experience. 

When was the last time you truly thanked your body, for all it provides.  Maybe today take a moment to just pause, see your own reflection and just simply say “thank you”

I woke up yesterday, hangover free, after celebrating my 44th year around the sun and my 3rd birthday sober - and I don’t think I’ve ever felt more grateful for this gift of sobriety.  Because that’s what it is….a gift I gave myself.

This year on my birthday I was in Maui.  Present with with kids.  With JP.  With myself.  In my body.  And really THERE.  All of me. 

It might not sound like a lot, but me being sober, and really present, changes everting.  My relationship with my kids, with JP, with myself.

It has truly been the best gift I’ve ever given myself and as I celebrated this 3rd birthday sober…I felt really proud.

If you ever considered taking a break from alcohol, even just for a little bit, you are not alone.  You don’t have to hit rock bottom to quit, or have a “problem”. It can simply be because it doesn’t feel good.  And you don’t have to make some big decision or declare that you’re “never drinking again”. It can simply be that today I’m choosing not to drink.  Because I just don’t want to. 

Either way, I’m behind you one billion percent.

I’m curious…what’s you’re relationship with alcohol…and how do you feel about it?? We may all have different stories when it comes to drinking, but none of us are alone in this…

Save for your next trip to Maui.

This morning J and I snuck out for an early sunrise meditation & hike along the Kapalua coastal trail (ps, we are huge lovers of @alltrails and use it to find hikes near us whenever we travel).

It was so nice being able to sit and meditate together as a couple (which is new for us). Especially in such a beautiful setting, watching the sunrise.  Have you ever sat and meditated with your partner or loved one?  Your kids?  Someone close to you?  It’s been really special being able to share something so important to me with the person I love.

…and for those of you traveling to Maui soon, the kapalua coastal trail is perfect for an easy hike.  But would love any other Maui recs u have.  It’s our first time here…and we love it. 

#morningmeditation #morningmeditations #hikemaui #alltrails #morninghike #morningwalks

I’ll be honest and say that this trip did not start off how I had imagined.  It wasn’t the five hour unexpected car ride up a mountain, or one of our kiddos getting sick, or having to change hotels because of a booking mix-up.  It wasn’t anything external.  instead it 100%….. me.  I was off.  I was tired and impatient.  Snapping at JP and the kids.  Being reactionary instead of calm and grounded.  And it set the tone for our first 48 hours here.  I tried blaming it on all the outside factors - but deep down I knew it was me.

And I was so dissapinted in myself.  I thought I was past a lot of this type of behavior/thinking/being.  But clearly I’m not (are any of us??)

It took me a good day or two to reset my energy and shake it off -but as soon as I did, the whole trip changed.  It’s wild how much our energy really does effect everything.  Every.  Thing. 

No real advice or thoughts.  All just to say this is a process.  Becoming self aware.  Owning up to our actions.  Being accountable for our energy.  Noticing our thoughts and patterns.  And then making choices.  Knowing that it’s all up to us…

Grateful for resets and do overs…even on vacation 🌴🤍

Back home from vacation and woke up today with a little bit of a pit in my stomach. 

I don’t know if it’s anxiety, reentry, or just that bitterseet feeling of saying goodbye to J and the kids as everyone rushed out the door.  But it caught me off guard this morning, and isn’t like me. 

It seems like everything is going too fast.  All of it.  And I’m realizng now that maybe I’m not always as present for it as I could be. 

I shared earlier how the beginning of our vacation felt a little chaotic for me, and I found myself snapping at J and the kids.  I was in my head, instead of in the moment.  And it showed in my actions.

As I woke up this morning and my mind rushed to all the things going on this week, all our responsibilities - I went right back to that same feeling.  Of being in my head.  Instead of here, in THIS moment.

And I want to change that.  So I’m making a conscious effort this week to slow down, and just be HERE with the kids.  J is travling all week, so I’m flying solo, and I’m going into it with no expectations on myself, the kids, each other.  And instead goint to try my hardest to live moment by moment and stay as grounded and as present as I can.

I’m curious if you’ve ever felt this way before?  And how you handle it…

I started making this reel yesterday and accidentally hit “publish” instead of save while I was editing it.  I had no idea it posted until I started getting some weird messages about my reel 😅🤦‍♀️. For a moment my heart sank and I was really embarrassed. 

But I immediately shook it off and just laughed.  We can be so hard on ourselves, for the silliest things - even IG posts.  For decades I cared about what people thought of me, or how I presented myself to the outside world.  As if I had to always have it all together.  Accidentally publishing that reel yesterday was a really good check in for me and a reminder to not take any of this so seriously….IG, myself and just life.  Sometimes just being able to laugh at yourself as say F@&# it is the best medicine

5 pregnancies, 4 healthy babies, one c-section & a myomectomy later - this chapter of my life comes to a close today.  Heading in for a hysterectomy that I feel so grateful for.  This organ has given me some of the happiest years of life.  But she has done her job.  So much gratitude for my body today and what it’s given me.  Today I honor her and all the life she’s given🤍

Grateful for my health, this life and what this next chapter holds

By the age of 60, 1 in 3 women will have a hysterectomy.  That’s 33% of you reading this.  And yet it’s never talked about. 

I haven’t written a blog post in a while, because I wasn’t sure what to say.  Today, I have a lot to say.

I’ve had so many mixed emotions since having this surgery done.  Days I feel grateful for my health and the ability to have this done.  Grateful for my strong body and her amazing ability to heal. 

And days I wonder if I made the right decision.  If somehow this could have been avoided if only something was done years before.  How I’m frustrated that this was the outcome after years of being told this is “normal”.

Days I’m angry and sad, wondering how in the hell did we get here?  How are so many women (especially in their 40s) having this procedure done.  Feeling like it’s their only option.  How is this sacred part of our body seen as disposable after a certain age?

How are we not taking better care of our sisters, our daughters and our mothers?  How are we not talking about this?  How are so many women suffering silently alone.  And how at 44 am I now the “one out of 3”. 

I want better us.

Too many thoughts for one Instagram post.  The full blog post is linked in my bio about my experience, what I’ve learned and what I hope for our daughters everywhere.

Taking a quick break to move my body between meditations.

I think so often people think about meditation as “not for them”. that they’re not good at it.  Or not sure what the point is.

Meditation is simply a way to return to wholeness.  To that connection to source that we lose.  That all lose.

Being in this human body we spend our whole lives in agony…with this void.  Searching for something that we can’t quite put into words, but we feel.  This subtle undercurrent of unease. 

And we fill it with everything.  Over controlling, being critical of others, food, alcohol, our weight.  Our images.  Our possessions.  Our children or our jobs.  Anything to somehow fill that void that we don’t even realize is there.

Meditation is simply a way home to the wholeness we’re all craving.  A way to remember you are not just connected to something bigger (source, god, the divine, whatever you want to call it), but that you ARE source.  That you are the devine.  That it lives within us, within ALL of us.  That we are all connected.  And that this reality you see in front of you.  This body or this place, this time or circumstance you find yourself is not real.  It’s just what your limited mind is capable of seeing. But you are so much more. 

Our minds keep us stuck and fixated on what’s right in front of us. The small stuff that we obsess over, that we aren’t even open to receive all that’s available to us.  That we are limitless.  And that  anything we desire is possible.

A truly life changing experience being here in Mexico on this retreat.

I sometimes wonder what this platform is used for.  Why I come on here and share.  And it always comes back to this intention of simply sharing a little of what I’ve learned/experienced in hopes that in some small way it can help one of you.

For those of you who have been curious about meditation but don’t “get it”, or need proof that it works, want to understand the science behind it more, or just feel like maybe somehow you’re not good at it, I can’t recommend looking into @drjoedispenza work enough. 

I promise you, with everything I believe, this work and this practice quite literally changes lives - and this week I’ve seen it and experienced for myself.  There is no one too old, too young, too sick, too busy, too rich, poor, tired to do this work.  And all you have to do is want it and be willing to start.
Ojai photo dump.  The best few days with friends who feel like family 🤍

I remember dreaming of days like this.  Riding bikes to lunch, meditations outside as the sun rose.  Pizza at the beach with a sunset.  Simple.  Easy.

Some days are just really good days.  Today was one of them.
weekend vibes 🌊⛰️

“….the bottom line is, right now, I know nothing.  Except that our dream is to call California home forever.  And knowing that with certainty feels really good. 

But besides that, there are only two other things about this move that I know for certain. 

One, our family needed more space.  We have that now. 

two, I miss the Ocean. Deeply. 

And right now, there’s no way to marry the two.  Instead, both coexist, simultaneously.  Heartache and loss for something I let go of and excitement and hope for something new. 

Yes. And. 

Me, as a parent, doing the thing I believe is best for our kids and our family as a whole.  And I, as an individual, missing the ocean and the life we created there.  Two very different needs.  Two parallel lines running alongside each other, never crossing.  Simply coexisting. 

Some things don’t have solutions. 

They just simply are. 

This move felt like that.  It just is.”

Full blog post linked in my bio.  And as always, thank you for all of your kind messages and words the past few days.  It feels as though so many of us are in a similar season of transition ✨🤍

I traveled with JP to Chicago for a work trip and to help celebrate some very special people in our lives.  We’ve really tried to say “yes” to more travel for things like this. I know that I say this from a seat of privilege (we do have help with our kids, we can afford it, I have someone I want to travel with), but the old me could have also easily said "no" to making this trip happen (and in fact wanted to cancel many times). We have a million reasons I could have stayed home - we're still unpacking a new house, all four kids have orientation at new schools (praying to make it back for a new high school event today 🤞), swim team and dance team auditions…..and simply just life as a family of six. And yet…..that's exactly why I needed to go. To reconnect with me for a few days, and equally my partner. We're so busy living our every day in the roles we play (and doing it damn well), but this right here is my most important role. simply being me.

A much needed few days away, but ready to head home

an impromptu unplanned live to share what’s on my mind, what I’m craving and what I want to create for all of us this season.  If you’re interested in learning more about the four week community and retreat, drop your name below with a little note and I’ll add you to our email last so you’ll be the first to know. 

And as always, thank you for being here 🤍

quick story about the power of our thoughts.

While we were hiking on our first day in Zion it began downpouring on us.  We had another few miles to walk.  We were all really tired, wet, hungry and now a little cranky (you get the picture).

Instead of letting the energy of our group fall, I started sharing with the kids this vision I had for our lunch.  We'd be sitting outside in the warm sun and I was going to eat the best veggie wrap.  It would be perfectly toasted, warm, and overflowing with a rainbow of veggies, some sprouts, avocado, and even a little smear of hummus.  I described it to the kids in detail, and as I did, I could really see it and taste it.  As if it was already there. My kids were of course annoyed and didn’t find talking about manifesting a warm lunch amusing. 

The thing was, I really believed that was what was going to be our lunch experience (even though I didn’t know one restaurant in Zion and we were stuck in the pouring rain)

But I kid you not, as if the universe was literally delivering my order, we got off the trail, the sun came out, and directly across the street from our parked car I spotted a little cafe. 

I walked in, asked the woman behind the counter…”you don’t happen to sell veggie wraps do you…?”. 

To which of course she replied “yes”! and described down a T the exact wrap I pictured.  My kids started laughing and said to the woman, “our mom just manifested that wrap.”😂

It sounds silly (and kind of embarrassing that my kids talk to strangers about manifesting). I get it.  It's just a wrap. 

But it's not…

We get so consumed and obsessed spending all our energy focused on what we DON’T want in our lives (the rain, to not be cold, hungry, tired), instead of what we DO want.

And whether we're conscious of it or not, the universe GIVES us MORE of whatever we put our attention on.

We literally are the creators of everything in our lives, from our sandwiches to our relationships, our homes, careers, the whole thing.

It really is that simple.  Your thoughts create your reality.  Our energy and our attention literally has the power to change our lives (and at times…even our lunch order 😅😉)

Welcome to Live Awake.  A four week journey to reawaken the deepest parts of your soul, to live with more ease, more abundance, more energy, more JOY.

You are designed to feel GOOD.  No matter what you believe, what you’ve been taught, or what your current life circumstances are - you are designed to feel good, in your body, your heat and your mind.  Well being wants to flow through you like water.

And yet…most of us aren’t living that way.

We’ve become so accustomed to running on adrenaline and stress hormones, always feeling fatigued, behind, stressed and somehow not enough.  Numbing ourselves along the way.  Constantly living with this undercurrent of dis-ease that we can’t quite put our finger on, but we know is there..

But it doesn’t have to be this way.

You can reawaken to the life you were meant to live.  You can reawaken to a new way of living, of thinking, of being.  One that feels good, at ease and is filled with energy and joy.

Our journey to Live Awake begins Monday 9/25.  Join us..

* click the link in my bio to learn more and see if this is right for you.

If you are ready to live a life of ease, abundance and joy.  If you are ready to live with more well being, energy and lightness - come join us as we begin to Live Awake.  We begin Monday 9/25.  Be in the room.

*comment Live Awake and I will personally send you all the information you need to join this special 4 week journey - or use the link in my bio to learn more.

What comes next is up to one thing…YOU ✨

We like to believe it’s going to be some big thing that happens and our lives are going to suddenly change.  But in reality, it’s the small, intentional choices we make every day that determine who we are and how we feel.

If you’re ready to begin making changes in your life, creating new habits, new routines, new ways of being…join us as we begin to Live AWAKE.  Our journey begins 9/25.  Doors are open.  Be in the room.

*for more information on how to join this incredible community, comment “Live Awake” below and I’ll personally send you all the details 😉

You don’t get what you want, you get whatever you ARE.  Right now, in this moment.  Whatever your energy is, that’s what you’re asking for more of.

If you want more ease and peace, are you able to cultivate peace and ease in your body, right now.

If you want more time and energy in your days, are you living right now with a mindset that there IS an abundance of time/energy available to you.

However you’re living, right now, is what you’re asking for more of

You only get to do this whole thing once.  Might as well make it extraordinary.  JP likes to tease me for being a little “extra” at times - and I can be.  I want my life to feel extraordinary.  I want to see as many sunrises and sunsets as I can.  I want to jump in as many waves, meditate in the morning glow, feel silk on my skin, have fresh flowers in my desk.  Yes, to all of it.  Because this life is meant to be enjoyed.  We deny ourselves pleasure and beauty all day long - for no reason other than we think it’s “too much” or unnecessary.  But feeling, seeing, touching beauty makes you come ALIVE.  And we need more people in this world who feel alive.

It’s never been about me.

Yes, it’s the work I personally do.  But it’s never actually been about me.  It’s so much bigger than that.

How we treat ourselves.  How we talk to ourselves.  How we think about about ourselves, is a direct mirror to how we think, talk and treat others.

It’s all connected.

When I first began this work, learning to live more mindfully, the first thing I noticed was how our home changed.  How my kids energy changed.  How my relationships began changing.

My whole world began slowly shifting, and I was at the epicenter of it.

The calm, peace and love I was strengthening inside of me was being reflected back

THAT is why I keep doing this work.

For far too long I let fear, worry about what people thought of me, and old stories keep me stuck living a life I knew didn’t align with who I was meant to be.

I didn’t know how to change.  I couldn’t see the big picture and didn’t know where to begin.  But I knew deep down something was “off”.

And I know I’m not alone.  In fact, I think most of us live this way.  Thinking things will get better “when…”. I’ll change careers “when…”. I’ll start taking better care of myself “when…”

And the list goes on.  Keeping ourselves stuck.  Never truly allowing ourselves to live or feel as radiant as we’re called to be

Which is why I’m so passionate about this work and reaching as many women as possible.

When we reawaken our own hearts- we invite all those around us to do the same. 

Live AWAKE begins September 25th.  Be in the room.

It’s amazing what happens when you decided you are worthy of an extraordinary life.  When you decide you no longer want to just survive the day, but you want to THRIVE in it.  You want to feel alive, and awake, and energized and soak up all the amazing beauty around you.

And the funny thing is…it usually doesn’t take much.  Instead it’s making the conscious choice to change just one thing…and then seeing how that one change affects everything else.

This was me on a walk yesterday.  I had a moment where I felt really overwhelmed. JPs been traveling nonstop for work, I’ve been solo parenting four kids (one who’s been home sick), launching a new course and just managing all things life with a family of six.

The thing is, moments like this happen all the time, for ALL of us.  No one is immune.  Rather than trying to avoid moments of overwhelm, I (try) to embrace them head-on. 

Just as we don’t judge the sky for the ever-changing weather, there’s no need to judge our human experience for our ever-changing emotions. 

What is important though, is what we do when we feel these moments surfacing so I thought I’d share a few things that have worked for me,...

- First and foremost, stop whatever you’re doing and just breathe. 
- Become compassionately curious with yourself.  Begin to notice what’s happening in your body.  Your heart, your stomach, your shoulders.  Where are you feeling it?  As you breathe, send your breath to those parts.  And just stay there.  Simply breathing.  Noticing.  compassionately observing.
- Move your body - go for a walk, shake it off, stretch, do a few sun salutations.  Do anything to get back into your body and just feel your body consciously moving. 
- Get out in nature - get your feet in the ground.  Touch the earth.  It has a powerful grounding effect that will immediately help your nervous system
- Look up - when we’re overwhelmed/stressed/angry our vision becomes very focused (usually on the negative). Just simply shifting your perspective (literally and physically) can help so much
- Write it out.  Putting pen to paper in moments like this can be so helpful in gaining clarity as to what you’re truly feeling
- And most importantly remind yourself that you are safe.  That these feelings are just as welcome/healthy as any other emotion.  Welcome it.  Allow yourself to feel it (without judgment or reaction), and then equally allow yourself to let it go. 

What about you?  What have you found to be helpful in moments like this...

The world reflects back to us whatever it is that we believe about ourselves, others, or the world around us.  Whether it’s lack, or abundance, good or bad.  We see whatever it is that we want to believe.

And often, we aren’t even aware of some of our subconscious beliefs. We’ve just played them on a loop for so long, they’re on auotpilot - and the world keeps reflecting it back to us. 

If you’re noticing a pattern, stuck in a thought loop, keep having the same experiences - maybe step back.  What are you subconsciously believing?  What are you subconsciously asking the universe for more of.

We create our own realities.  If we don’t like something - maybe it’s time to change our thoughts.

I’m a big believer in rituals.  They don’t have to be anything big.  Just a small intentional moment incorporated into my day - especially on moments like this, the fall equinox.

Equinox’s are special days because they mark moments of harmony and balance in the earth.  Equal parts day and night.

I marked the day by getting out for a sunrise hike followed by a dip in the pacific (if you really knew me, you’d know that the ocean is my second home). 

But here are a few simple things you can do today, right at home, to take advantage of this special day.

- get out in nature.  Take off your shoes.  Feel your feet in the earth and just breathe.
- light a candle, open a journal and take a moment to reflect on what you’re grateful for today, right now in this moment
- take a bath, jump in a river, lake, ocean, whatever - get your body in water.  Feel it surround you.  Notice the energy and feel yourself being held in the water
- burn sage or Paulo santo, say a prayer in your heart giving thanks for the abundance and harmony in your life
- mediate.  It doesn’t have to be anything fancy.  Grab a pillow or cushion, get on the floor and just witness your breath.  Feel the equal inhale matched by the equal exhale.  Feel the balance in your breath and your body.

Any other ideas…? Any rituals you love I should include?

It sounds so simple. “Slow down. Notice. Breathe.” And yet it seems to be so hard for so many of us. 

We all carry these old stories of lack when it comes to time. “I don’t have the time..”, “I’m too busy…”. “When life slows down…”.

I get it.  I lived that way for most of my adult life.  My nervous system always in fight or flight.  Rushing from one thing to the next.  Living off of stress hormones and adrenaline - and to be honest - not ever aware that was how I was living.

I have news… life is never going to slow down.  In fact, I’m pretty sure it’s speeding up.

You don’t “find” time, you create it.

Decide what matters to you.  And then carve a life around THAT.  A calm mind.  A relaxed body.  An open heart.  If that’s what you want, then it starts by slowing down.  Noticing.  Witnessing yourself.  Seeing the world (and I mean really seeing it). 

Your body is begging for it 🤍

There is not such thing as tomorrow.  All we have is right now.  We will never feel ready.  Things will never feel perfect.  It will never be the “right time”. Those things don’t exist.  And you might be scared out. Of. Your. Mind.

But you do it anyway.  Make the move.  Quit the job.  Write the book.  Start the new business.  Leave the marriage/start the marriage.  Have the baby. 

You just have to hit go.  And start.  And the the next day, do it again. And again.  And again.  And you keep taking the next aligned action and see where it takes you. 

But I promise you - nothing happens if nothing happens.

Today is that day.

I don’t talk about my sobriety enough in here. It’s a huge part of my life, and in many ways I think my super power.  But it wasn’t easy getting started, or even making the decision to quit.  It was something I had thought about for years, but never felt ready.  I see it as a real option for myself. (Other people, sure. “Me”, not so much).

Here’s what helped me the most in those first few months…

 🤍 asking for help.  Sharing my intention and how scared I was (afraid I’d fail) with those closest to me was crucial those first few months.  I needed cheerleaders. Not people who were going to question me, or who I had to explain myself too.  Which meant making some adjustments to who I gave my time to.  It was a real wake up call for me on who truly wanted to best “for me” (not just who I made comfortable). Not everyone i going to get it.  And that’s ok.  It’s not their life - it’s yours 

 🤍 getting out and moving every day.  My body had been holding on to a lot of tension over the years.  Drinking had numbed some of that - so when I first became sober, a lot of stuff started coming up for me.  And it may for you too.  Moving (yoga, dancing, walking, whatever) every day helped clear a lot of it out.  It was my physical release.
 
🤍 rewarding myself.  When I fist became sober it felt like I was “giving up” a lot.  But in reality, I was gaining so much more than I even knew.  It was really important that right away I focused on the good I was now cultivating in my life, and I double downed on it.  I created new routines that felt indulgent.  Rewarding myself. 

🤍 I stopped asking for permission for people to get me and I started living life for me.  I stopped explaining my sobriety, and pretty quickly every other choice in my life.  I started feeling empowering, that I knew how to take care of me, better than anyone else, and I stopped looking to everyone else for validation and approval and it felt damn good

What about you.  What’s helped you the most in your sobriety…

right now, we find ourselves in what is supposed to be the season of love, joy and peace.  And yet, as I look at the world around us, I can’t help but wonder if that’s how most of us are feeling - and I’m reminded once again that how we treat ourselves, is how we treat each other and the world around us.

If we can’t be nonjudgmental, loving, compassionate, and kind to ourselves, than we can’t give that to each other.

And right now, more than ever, the world is begging for us to love ourselves.  To forgive ourselves.  To let the shame, comparison, and judgment of ourselves go.

So that we can give that same gift to each other.

We are so good at beating ourselves up.  Silently judging and shaming ourselves.  When we look in the mirror, when we’re impatient with our kids/spouse, when we lay our head on the pillow at night and we catalog all that we did (or didn’t do), all that we ate, all that we said.

And that energy, that shame and judgment, doesn’t stay just with us.  It bleeds into our lives. Into our families.  Our communities.  Our world.

We must first love ourselves,
To love each other.

We must first forgive ourselves,
To forgive each other,

We must first liberate ourselves,
To liberate each other. 

This season the greatest gift we can give each other, and the world, is simply to love, forgive, and accept ourselves.

It can be so easy this time of year to get caught up in comparing ourselves to others.  People’s highlight reels with our very real messy lives.  And it leaves us feeling empty.  like we didn’t quite do enough.  Are enough.

And I just want to remind you that none of that is real.  Nothing you see here on social media, or at the school holiday party or at your neighbors cookie exchange.  Is real.  We present ourselves in a way we “want” to be seen to protect ourselves.  But please know, that everyone you see here, everyone you meet out in the world, is fighting the same messy battle. 

Just trying to survive.  They too have strained relationships with their parents or kids.  They’re struggling with body issues or wondering if they have enough money to cover holiday gifts this year…

We’re all just doing our best to survive.  To find a little moment of joy.  To find some peace.

Go easy on yourself.  You’ve made it though another year.  Be proud.  Hold your head up high.  You’re more than enough 🤍

Just because this time of year has always been stressful, doesn’t mean it has to be that way.

You get to choose how these next few weeks ago.  You can rewrite how you do the holidays.  At any point.  You can rewrite the story. 

Prioritize the things that truly fill you up. 

Take care of yourself.  Nurture yourself.  Be good to yourself.

There is no better gift we can give each other and the world right now than learning how to LOVE and nourish ourselves.

Because how we treat ourselves, is how we treat the WORLD 🤍✨

The decision to live a life without alcohol can be one of the scariest decisions you can make.

It takes many of us years to finally be able to make this choice - something I struggled for almost a decade with.  Always moderating.  Counting drinks.  Dry January and sober September with months of over consuming in between.  It was exhausting. 

I knew deep down I hated how alcohol made me feel - but it was everywhere.  Everyone I knew drank.  It was at every event.  Every holiday.  Every girls dinner.

I’ve been sober now 3 years (today). And here’s what helped me in those first few months…
- trusting my intuition.  Allowing my inner voice to be louder than my fear or other people’s judgements
- remembering that I owed NO ONE and explanation
- took it one day at a time. Didn’t allow myself to worry about the “wedding next month” or the girls trip later that summer.  I just focused on today.  One day at a time
- had a plan.  A drink I’d order.  The exit plan to leave a party when people were too drunk. 
- rewarded myself.  I celebrated all the “firsts”. And began noticing all that was being ADDED to my life, not taken away.
- be honest.  With yourself and those you love.  This was really hard for me.  Just this past year I had to have a hard conversation with my family about the holidays and how we wouldn’t have alcohol at our home on xmas

- you can find more tips in a full blog post on my website.

Remember - you have ONE life.  Just one.  How you use it is up to YOU.  It’s never too late to make changes and start living in a way that feels really good to you. 

And for those just getting started - I’m behind you one million percent.
For those who are sober - curious what helped you the most in those first few months of sobriety.

so that we may ALL be at ease

- dinner at @sanysidroranch is a must.  The grounds are stunning and the food/service match its beauty.  A truly magical spot worth the hype
- lunch at @helenaavenuebakery for those who appreciate amazing croissants (and their salads/sandwich’s are on par with the bread)
- breakfast at @mercimontecito - stay to shop a little at the @montecitocountrymart (lots of cute stores)
- quick stop in Summerland at @thewellsummerland and @porch_summerland for gorgeous home goods (my dream backyard)
- @dartcoffeeco best coffee in town
- and of course the beautiful beaches (we probably liked the beach at Summerland the best, followed by mesa lane). 
- oh and we stayed at the cutest @airbnb that is perfect for families (amazing location and the house is perfection) @mesabeachhouse 

I think that covers it - Hope the helps for you next getaway 🤍

When we decide to move the west coast, it was for moments like this.  To be able to pack up the car on January 1st and go be together out in nature.

This was our fist time camping as a family - and my first time sleeping in a tent, ever.  And I can’t believe I’m saying this, but I’m kind of hooked.

We had the BEST time.  Sleeping listening to the sound of the ocean, waking up with the sun and my kids all cuddled and cozy in a tent.  There was something about the simplicity and pureness about camping - it’s just you and the elements and it humbles you in the best way possible.

For those of you “non campy” people who’ve debated ever giving it a try - I will tell you that it’s so much better than you can imagine. 

And for those of you in California looking to plan your own trip - we camped at sycamore canyon campgrounds at @pointmugustatepark - and would hands down go back. 

#familycampingtrip #campingwithkids #familieswhotravel #californiahiking

I haven’t really talked about this much on here, but 6 months ago our family moved from the beach to the suburbs of L.A.  And pretty quickly knew it was a mistake.

We moved because of me.  And because of fear.

I let an old value system creep in and tell me what I thought my life shold look like.  How to raise my kids.  What was needed.  What I should value.  Space.  A yard.  A traditional home.

I was scared we could’t make the beach work.  I let old stories around scarcity come out.  How our family is too large.  The homes too small.  The prices too steep and our bank account too shallow.  I couldn’t see it.  And I let fear guide me. 

We dind’t leave the beach becuase I wanted to - we moved because I was too scared not to.  I second guessed myself.  Didn’t trust my intuition. 

I thought I had changed. That I had left all those old traditional mindsets behind when I left Chicago.  But old habits die hard. 

Realizing you’ve made a mistake (espeically when kids are involved) is not easy.  Guilt.  Shame.  Fear. all get very loud.

I don’t know what’s next for our family or where we’ll end, and as a mom of four (with two of our kids in very formative years) that can feel a little scary.  I have to remind myself that the messages society gives us around what kids “need” isn’t actually what they need at all.  And that our kids are more than just “ok”, that they’re thriving.  And that I am too.  Even in those moments when we feel a little unrooted.  That this too is part of the process. 

It turns out that even though I shed an old home in Chicago almost two years ago, I’m still learning to shed old ways of thinking. 

But throughout this process over the past 6 months…here’s what I’ve learned.

Nothing is permanent.  You can always change your mind.  You can change your space, your job, your relationships, your habits, your thoughts.  You always have a choice.  Nothing is permanent 

Just because you’re an adult, doens’t mean you have the answers.  No one really does.

What you once valued, does not have to be what you value now.

The only stability my kids need is me.
